{
  "text": "The experiment was designed to collect data from multiple populations of silver leaf nightshade (Solanum eleaegnifolium) from one of its major native ranges-South Texas. S. eleaegnifolium is a perennial herb native to southwest, west-central USA and Northern Mexico ( [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ; Fig. 1 ). S. eleaegnifolium colonize disturbed areas, outcompete co-inhabiting plants for resources, and have both structural (spines, trichomes) and chemical defenses (secondary metabolites that are toxic to livestock), making it hard to eradicate [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The species has colonized all over the world and is a grave concern in many countries. Although data on growth and other functional traits of this species has been collected from other native and invasive ranges, we currently lack data from one of its major native range in South Texas [CITATION_6] .",
